Motor control

  • Previously, we have described skeletal muscle contractions as voluntary (to distinguish from cardiac andsmooth muscle)
  • However, skeletal muscle contractions and movement of the limbs can be further classified
    • Voluntary
      • Initiated at will
      • Integrated in the cerebral cortex
      • E.g. playing piano
    • Rhythmic
      • Initiation and termination is voluntary
      • Integrated in the spinalcord withhigher brain input required
      • E.g. walking or running
    • Reflex
      • Initiated by sensory receptors
      • Integrated in the spinal cord or brain stem without higher brain modulation
      • E.g. Knee jerk, cough or postural reflexes

Motor Control

  • The intention to contract a skeletal muscle begins in the motor association(premotor) area of the frontal lobe, it generates a movement plan/program
  • This plan is transmitted to the precentral gyrus (primary motor area) of thefrontal lobe
    • From here, neurons (upper motor neurons) send signals to the brainstemand spinal cord (they form corticospinal tracts)
  • In the brainstem or spinal cord, the fibres from the upper motor neuronssynapse with lower motor neurons
    • Lower motor neurons innervate the skeletal muscles

Motor Control

  • The basal nuclei and cerebellum are also important for motor control
    • Basal nuclei
      • Involved in onset and offset of movements
      • Repetitive hip and shoulder movements during walking
      • Highly practised movements carried out with little thought (e.g. writing, tying shoes laces)
      • There is a feedback circuit from the cerebrum to the basal nuclei to the thalamus and back to thecerebrum

Motor Control

  • The basal nuclei and cerebellum are also important formuscle control
    • Cerebellum
      • Learning motor skills
      • Maintains muscle tone and posture, smooths musclecontractions, coordinates eye and body movements,and helps coordinate movements at multiple joints(e.g. shoulder and elbow while throwing)
      • Cerebellum acts as a comparator to correct muscleperformance to intended movement
        • Receives information from upper neurons aboutintended movement
        • Receives information from proprioceptors inmuscles and joints
        • Receives information from eyes and inner ears

Silverthorn, Human Physiology

Reflex movements

  • Reflex movements are rapid andinvoluntary contractions of skeletalmuscle
    • They require a stimulus
    • They are quick (minimal synapticdelay)
    • Involuntary (you maybe become awareof the movement, but it is not part ofthe reflex)
    • Stereotyped (the same contractionevery time)

What happens when there a disruption to theneuromuscular system?

Peripheral nerve regeneration

  • When a nerve fibre is cut, the fibre distal to the injury cantsurvive because it is incapable of protein synthesis
    • Schwann cells will degenerate as well because theydepend on the neuron for maintenance
  • Macrophages clean up tissue debris at the point of injuryand beyond
  • The soma will swell and endoplasmic reticulum breaks upso the chromatophilic substance disperses
    • Some cells will die at this stage
    • But often, the axon stump sprouts multiple growthprocesses

Figure 12.10

Peripheral nerve regeneration

  • Schwann cells, basal lamina and neurilemma forma regeneration tube near the injury
    • More distal sites degenerate
  • Growth processes eventually re-establish synapticconnections with target cells

Figure 12.10

Spinal cord injury

  • Spinal cord injury is any injury to the spinal cord via blunt or penetrating trauma
    • In USA, approximately 10,000 people newly paralysed each year
  • Involves a primary and secondary process
    • Primary process involves the destruction of cells by the traumatic event via energy transfer to thespinal cord, spinal cord deformation and/or persistent spinal cord compression
      • Cause immediate cell death, axonal disruption, vascular changes and metabolic changes
    • Secondary process involves a wave of tissue death by necrosis and apoptosis that can last minutes todays/weeks/months
      • Not well understood, but often more damaging than the primary process
      • Haemorrhages in appear in the grey matter, whereas white matter becomes swollen
      • Lack of blood leads to necrosis
      • Apoptosis of glial cells in spinal cord causes demyelination and further cell death of neurons
  • Necrosis of the central grey matter and astrocyte degeneration leads to the development of scar tissue
    • Scar tissue prevents axonal regeneration

Spinal nerves

  • Spinalnerves and any nerve that arises fromthe spinal cord and pass throughintervertebral foramina (or the gap betweenthe spine and cranium)
    • There are 31 pairs of spinal nervescorresponding to the vertebra of the spine

Figure 13.11

Myotomes and dermatomes

  • A myotome is the group of muscles that a single spinal nerveinnervates
  • A dermatome is an area of skin that is mainly supplied by asingle spinal nerve

Figure 13.22

Functional Electrical Stimulation (FES)

  • FES is the application of electrical current to excitable tissue to supplement or replacefunction that is lost in neurologically impaired individuals
    • This broad definition covers devices such as a cochlear implant and a cardiacpacemaker
    • In this subject, we will be considering FES for restoration of limbfunction or skeletalmuscle functionin spinal cordinjury
  • Spinal cord injury prevents action potentials from propagating from the brain to themuscles
  • For effective FES, the lower motor neuron, neuromuscular junction and muscle cellsmust be healthy and intact
    • In some cases, the muscles can be directly stimulated

Electrical activation of the neuromuscularsystem

  • Electrical pulses applied to nerves and muscles canelicit action potentials
    • Stimulating electrode creates an electric fieldthat can depolarise plasma membranes in closeproximity
    • This depolarisation of the membrane activatesvoltage-gated sodium channels to generate anaction potential

Peckham, 2005, Functional Electrical Stimulationfor Neuromuscular Applications. Figure 1.

Electrical activation of the neuromuscularsystem is different to physiological activation

  • In a nerve fibre with 100s or 1000s of axons, large-diameter axons are activated with less current(supplied by the stimulating electrode) than smaller diameter axons
    • This is due to:
      • Wider spacing between nodes of Ranvier produces larger induced transmembrane voltagechanges
      • Large diameter axons providing less resistance to internal current flow
    • Remember the physiological size principal for the recruitment of motor neurons (Lecture 4.1 orHennemansSize Principle)
      • Or remember spatial summation for smaller neurons with smaller cell bodies
    • What are the consequences of activating larger motor neurons before smaller motor neurons?
  • Stimulating the middle of an axon will generate an action potential that propagates in both directions
    • No functional significance as retrogradely propagating action potential will dissipate at the cell body

Electrical activation of the neuromuscularsystem: Stimulation parameters

  • Electrodes create an electric field that depolarises excitable membranes by delivering a waveform ofelectrical current pulses
    • Pulse frequency
      • If the pulse frequency is low, the muscle will display a series of twitches
      • If the pulse frequency is high, the muscle will display a fused contraction but also quickly inducesmuscle fatigue
      • A pulse frequency of 10-25 Hz is often used as a minimum to produce summation of twitches andavoid muscle fatigue
    • Pulse duration
      • Can be altered to change contraction strength
    • Pulse amplitude
      • Can be altered to change contraction strength
    • The waveform can be either monophasic or biphasic
      • Biphasic is often used (particularly for implanted electrodes) because the secondary positivepulse balances the charge, which reduces damage from electrochemical process at electrode-tissue interface

Electrical activation of the neuromuscularsystem: Stimulation parameters

  • Stimulators are designed to regulate either current or voltage
    • With voltage-regulated stimulation, the stimulator output is a voltage, so the current supplied isdependent on the impedance at the electrode interface (Ohms Law)
      • Useful for electrodes on the skin because if the electrode dries or loses contact, impedanceincreases and therefore current decreases
        • Reduces possibility of skin burns
    • With current-regulated stimulation, the stimulator output is a current, so the voltage supplied isdependent on the impedance
      • So the charge delivered is constant (not affects by changes in tissue load)
      • Often used with implanted electrodes because it is more likely to produce similar responses inthe muscle

Electrical activation of the neuromuscularsystem: Electrode configuration

Peckham, 2005, Functional Electrical Stimulationfor Neuromuscular Applications. Figure 2.

FES examples: Hand Grasp

  • Ness H200 Hand Rehabilitation System
    • For individuals with C5 tetraplegia or hemiplegia caused by stroke
      • Still requires the use of arm or upper arm
    • Stimulates hand movements to allow patients to grasp objects
      • Extension
        • Extensordigitorum
        • Extensorpollicisbrevis
      • Flexion
        • Flexordigitorumsuperficialis
        • Flexorpollicislongus
      • Opposition of the thumb
        • Thethenargroup
    • https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mKoUuNswvMI
  • Many other examples of hand grasp, such as Bionic Glove,FESMateand Freehand

bioness.com

FES examples: Footdrop

  • L300 Go System
    • A footdrop system that stimulates common peroneal nerve and subsequentlytibialis anterior to cause dorsiflexion of the foot
    • Uses 3D motion detection and machine learning to detect gait events andproduce a more natural walk
  • ActiGait
    • An implantable footdrop system

l300go.com

Hausmannet al. Journal ofNeuroEngineeringandRehabilitation (2015) 12:100

FES examples: Standing and AmbulationSystems

  • Standing systems
    • Stimulating the quadriceps and glutei muscles for kneeand hip extension
  • Ambulation systems
    • Stimulate the quadriceps and glutei muscleson one leg
    • Use stimulation of the peroneal nerve to elicit a flexionwithdrawal reflex of the hip, knee and ankle
      • Substitutes the swing phase of gait

Triolo, et al.

Arch Phys MedRehabil. 2018 99(2): 289298.

doi:10.1016/j.apmr.2017.08.470.

FES examples: Bladder, bowel and sexualfunctions

  • Spinal anterior root stimulation (SARS) system
    • With spinal cord injury, of all the body functions lost, micturitionand continence is of the highest priority
      • Due to infections and blood pressure issues can createsignificant health issues
      • Also personal and social implications
    • Stimulation electrodes are placed intradural on the sacral ventralroots (motor neurons)
    • Results in simultaneous contraction of detrusors smooth musclesskeletal muscle of the pelvic floor
    • Pulsatile stimulation with long intervals allows micturitionbecause the skeletal muscle relaxes rapidly, while the smoothmuscle reacts slowly, producing post-stimulus voiding

Zaer, et al.ActaNeurochir160,13771384 (2018).

https://doi.org/10.1007/s00701-018-3557-1

FES examples: Respiration

  • Avery Mark IV Phrenic Pacemaker
    • For spinal cord injury,Ondinessyndrome (issues with autonomicnervoussytem), central sleepapneaor diaphragm paralysis
    • Requires residual function in the diaphragm, lungs and phrenic nerves
    • External transmitter sends radio frequency energy to the implant,which converts them into stimulating pulses
    • Stimulates the phrenic nerve causing the diaphragm to contract,resulting in inhalation of air
    • When the stimulation stops, diaphragm relaxes and exhalation occurs

Ducko,Innovations 2011;6:289297
